1 (B) cryptocurrency;
2 (C) financial technology; or
3 (D) digital innovation technology; and
4 (iii) two additional members, one of whom is a broker-dealer regulated under Title 30, chapter 10;
5 and
6 (e) five members appointed by the governor, including:
7 (i) two members with experience in:
8 (A) blockchain;
9 (B) cryptocurrency;
10 (C) financial technology; or
11 (D) digital innovation technology; and
12 (ii) three additional members, one of whom is from a financial service institution regulated under
13 Title 32, chapter 1.
14 (3) The members described in subsections (2)(c)(i) and (2)(d)(i) shall serve as cochairpersons of
15 the task force.
16 (4) Members must be appointed within 30 days after [the effective date of this act]. All member
17 terms occur from the time of appointment until December 31, 2026. If a vacancy occurs in the membership of
18 the task force, the member must be replaced in the same manner in which the original appointment was made.
19 (5) Members may not receive reimbursement for salary or expenses.
20 (6) (a) A majority of the members of the task force constitutes a quorum.
21 (b) The action of a majority of a quorum constitutes an action of the task force.
22 (7) The task force shall:
23 (a) develop knowledge and expertise regarding issues pertaining to blockchain, financial
24 technology, and digital innovation technology; and
25 (b) develop and introduce recommendations regarding policy pertaining to:
26 (i) the promotion in the state of the adoption of blockchain, financial technology, and digital
27 innovation;
28 (ii) the development of nonfinancial incentives for industries in the state related to blockchain,
